Tschlin Village Phone. The village of Tschlin in Switzerland is said to be so quiet that when the community’s central telephone rings, some resident or other will always answer. So the idea here was to encourage people around the world to call the phone & see what happened – any call that went unanswered won the caller a free holiday to Tschlin. It worked pretty well too – the village’s 166 residents fielded 30,000 calls + 65 people won a holiday. Courtesy of Dan Bevis @ LB Frisk.

Third-hand smoke causes serious health problems. While first-hand smoke refers to the smoke inhaled by a smoker and second-hand smoke to the exhaled smoke and other substances emanating from the burning cigarette that can get inhaled by others, third-hand smoke is the second-hand smoke that gets left on the surfaces of objects, ages over time and becomes progressively more toxic.

This anti-smoking advertisement from ash.org uses depictions of children’s objects (crayons) to elicit emotions of shame and guilt in smokers with children or young siblings. It catches the viewer’s attention with the striking image of crayons-turned-cigarettes and includes statistics about the increased likelihood of smoking when parents and siblings smoke. Is this an effective campaign? What could be done to make it more effective? Does it help smokers find resources to quit smoking?
Every smoker is aware of the damage their habit causes, but to finally quit, that extra push is usually needed. So here we bring you some of the most innovative anti-smoking ads ever created.
